{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512153"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:51:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:51:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11854"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11854"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.23,0.14,0.02,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65201"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4454"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50638"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11605"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44729"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65201"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being found unconscious in his garage. His wife reports he was working on his car with the engine running and the garage door almost shut. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is 6 (E1 V2 M3) and his mucous membranes have a cherry-red appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measurement of carboxyhaemoglobin level","Hyperbaric oxygen therapy","Non-rebreather mask with 15 L/min oxygen","Urgent intensive care review","Intubation and ventilation with 100% oxygen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of severe carbon monoxide poisoning: reduced consciousness after exposure to combustion products in an enclosed space, with cherry-red mucous membranes and falsely normal oxygen saturation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and ventilation with 100% oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate management. With a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 6, the patient requires immediate airway protection. High-flow oxygen also reduces the half-life of carboxyhaemoglobin from 4-5 hours to approximately 1 hour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement of carboxyhaemoglobin level\u003C/strong\u003E would confirm the diagnosis but should not delay treatment in a patient with clear history and examination findings consistent with severe carbon monoxide poisoning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperbaric oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered as a subsequent treatment to further reduce the carboxyhaemoglobin half-life to 20-30 minutes, but the immediate priority is airway protection via intubation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-rebreather mask with 15 L/min oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient in this case as it does not protect the airway in a patient with severely reduced consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent intensive care review\u003C/strong\u003E will be required but should not delay immediate airway management in the Emergency Department.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarbon monoxide has 200-250 times greater affinity for haemoglobin than oxygen. Pulse oximetry is unreliable as it cannot distinguish between oxyhaemoglobin and carboxyhaemoglobin, leading to falsely normal readings. The cherry-red appearance of mucous membranes is a late finding seen in severe poisoning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbon monoxide poisoning should be suspected in patients found unconscious in enclosed spaces with combustion engines","Pulse oximetry is unreliable in carbon monoxide poisoning as it falsely shows normal oxygen saturation","Immediate airway protection with intubation and 100% oxygen is required in carbon monoxide poisoning with reduced consciousness"],"references":["Buckley NA, Juurlink DN, Isbister G, Bennett MH, Lavonas EJ. Hyperbaric oxygen for carbon monoxide poisoning. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews 2011, Issue 4. Art. No.: CD002041. DOI: 10.1002/14651858.CD002041.pub3. Accessed 05 July 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50638"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50638"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:38:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:39:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4454"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"ques